MUNITIES -- t11. Love Trumps Hate: Community Caretaking in an Era of Mass Deportation -- t12. Helping Refugees in Rural Germany: Ambivalences of Compassion -- t13. Toward a Theory of Climate Praxis: Confronting Climate Change in a World of Struggle -- t14. The Discovery of Contamination: Forever Chemicals and the Temporality of Critique -- t15. Democracy Without Demos: The Disappearance of the Working Class and the Rise of Abstention in French Political Life -- tPART FOUR. REFLEXIVE PERSPECTIVES -- t16. New Technologies and the Moral Economy of White Nationalism -- t17. “The Only Way Out Is Through”: Anthropology as Critical Praxis in Times of Crisis -- t18. Social Movements and Social Theory -- t19. The Invisible Rebellion: Working People Under the New Capitalist Economy -- t20. Conspiracy Theories as Ambiguous Critique of Crisis -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe word “crisis” denotes a break, a discontinuity, a rupture—a moment after which the normal order can continue no longer. Yet our political vocabulary today is suffused with the rhetoric of crisis, to the point that supposed abnormalities have been normalized. How can the notion of crisis be rethought in order to take stock of—and challenge—our understanding of the many predicaments in which we find ourselves?Instead of diagnosing emergencies, Didier Fassin, Axel Honneth, and an assembly of leading thinkers examine how people experience, interpret, and contribute to the making of and the response to critical situations. Contributors inquire into the social production of crisis, evaluating a wide range of cases on five continents through the lenses of philosophy, sociology, anthropology, political science, history, and economics. Considering social movements, intellectual engagements, affected communities, and reflexive perspectives, the book foregrounds the perspectives of those most closely involved, bringing out the immediacy of crisis. Featuring analysis from below as well as above, from the inside as well as the outside, Crisis Under Critique is a singular intervention that utterly recasts one of today’s most crucial—yet most ambiguous—concepts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCrises. 0aCritical theory. 0aSocial conflict. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acapitalism.  acritical theory.  aeconomics.  ahistory.  aphilosophy.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  aprotest.  asociology.  aunrest.1 aAmaya, Hector, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrennan, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCelikates, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Daniel Aldana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordero, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDefossez, Anne-Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobler, Gregor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassin, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassin, Didier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHonneth, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonneth, Axel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIdris, Murad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhayyat, Munira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchesi, Aldo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMattei, Clara El